Single Variable Plots¶

Histogram with KDE¶

Pros: Good simple, very commonly understood plot for describing the distribution, with an added best fit curve.
Cons: Gives a sense of the distribution but doesn't put numbers on the mean, quartiles.

Boxplot with Swarm¶

Pros: Richer information than the histogram - i.e. mean, quartiles and 10/90the percientiles are clear. The swarm captures even more detail showing all the actual data points.
Cons: Not as well known as the histogram.

Violin¶

Pros: Combines the familiar historgram view and a box-plot-like line plot, for a similar richness of description to the boxxplot + swarm.
Cons: Not as well known as the histogram.

Histogram with best-fit Gamma curve¶

Pros: Same commonly understood historgram, with a visual overlay of a gamma curve, showign that it "kinda is like a gamma."
Cons: Requires some additional explanation, as compared to the historgram and KDE. Might even be confused for the historgram + KDE without explanation.

  • Rising HDI seems to correlate to rising suicide rates

Observations¶

  • The relationship seems to hold for men and women
  • The violin plot does s great job of showing the distribution shape differences between gender
  • The categorical scatterplot is not all that useful here
  • The line plot is best for showing the trend across categories - since these categories have directionality.
  • The seaborn swarm plot doesn't work well with this size of data, it seems. It seems to break jupyter - i.e. nothing will execute after trying to execute the swarm.

# Create one master plot that gives insight into the variables and their interrelationships, including:
#   Probability distributions
#   Bivariate relationships
#   Whether the distributions or the relationships vary across groups
#   Accompany your plot with a written description of what you see.

#one categorical: age
#four continuous: suicide rate, hdi, gdp per capita, population

#probability distribuitons

sns.set_style("white")
plt.rc("axes.spines", top=False, right=False)
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 15))
plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.2, hspace=0.4)

plt.subplot(3,2,1)
male_sr = su.loc[su["sex"] == "male"]["suicides/100k pop"].dropna()
female_sr = su.loc[su["sex"] == "female"]["suicides/100k pop"].dropna()
#ax1 = sns.boxplot(male_sr)
ax1 = sns.boxplot(x="sex", y="suicides/100k pop", data=su)
ax1.set_ylim(0,80)
plt.title("country suicide rates are skewed low, with a dramatic difference by gender")

plt.subplot(3,2,2)
ax2 = sns.distplot(su["HDI for year"].dropna())
plt.title("country HDI's are skewed high")

#Bi-variate relationships
plt.subplot(3,2,3)
ax6 = sns.regplot(x="gdp_per_capita ($)", y="HDI for year", data = su, scatter_kws={"alpha":.02}, line_kws={"color":"r"})
plt.title("GDP/capita's positive impact on GDP tails off at $40-60k")

plt.subplot(3,2,4)
sns.kdeplot(su["population"], su["gdp_per_capita ($)"], shade=True, shade_lowest=False)
plt.title("countries are clustered heavily at low gdp/capital and population")

plt.subplot(3,2,5)
sns.lineplot(x="hdi_bin", y="suicides/100k pop", data=su, hue="sex")
plt.title('suicide rates rise with HDI')

plt.subplot(3,2,6)
ordered_age = ["5-14 years", "15-24 years", "25-34 years", "35-54 years", "55-74 years", "75+ years"]
sns.stripplot(x="suicides/100k pop", y="age", data=su, hue="sex", order=ordered_age)
ax3 = sns.boxplot(x="suicides/100k pop", y="age", data=su,whis=np.inf, color="white", order=ordered_age)
plt.title('suicide rates mean and variance rise steadily with age')

plt.show()
